body:
I don't know, but Eliza has done something to the fetch method! Below I explain why!

I am trying to add the image upload feature to the Twitter client. I have passed data as `agent-twitter-client` library accepts, but when I call it I get this error 
```
 {"errors":[{"code":38,"message":"media parameter is missing."}]}
```

I did extensive debugging. I cloned the `agent-twitter-client` and loaded it as a local dependency in eliza package.json.
```
        "agent-twitter-client": "file:/Users/amin/Downloads/agent-twitter-client",
```
I put some logs at upload points in the `agent-twitter-client` and executed its tests, including image uploading. 
I could upload images by running this repo tests. But when I try to use it through eliza, I got the aforementioned error.

It's the upload point in the `agent-twitter-client`

```ts
    console.log({
      uploadUrl,
      p: {
        method: 'POST',
        headers,
        body: form,
      },
    });

    const response = await fetch(uploadUrl, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers,
      body: form,
    });
```

The console.log output is the same for running the `agent-twitter-client` test and the Eliza agent.


**Update:**
I have come closer to this conclusion by writing a simple nodejs app and run it directly:
```js

import fs from 'fs';

async function main() {
    const uploadUrl = 'https://upload.twitter.com/1.1/media/upload.json';
    const mediaData = fs.readFileSync(
        "/Users/amin/Downloads/agent-twitter-client/test-assets/test-image.jpeg"
    );

    const form = new FormData();
    form.append('media', new Blob([mediaData]));
    const headers = {
        authorization: 'Bearer ******************,
        cookie: 'auth_token=****************; guest_id=v1%**********',
        'x-csrf-token': '************************'
    }

    const response = await fetch(uploadUrl, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers,
      body: form,
    });

    if (!response.ok) {
      console.log('Upload response was not ok:', await response.text());
      throw new Error(await response.text());
    }

    const data = await response.json();
    console.log(`media upload data: ${JSON.stringify(data, null, 2)}`);
}


main().then(() => process.exit(0));

```

It works correctly when I run it directly. But when I copy the same code as an independent function and call it inside eliza, again I get that error
```
   {"errors":[{"code":38,"message":"media parameter is missing."}]} 
```
